column28: One of the main complains from GIS users of projects like QGIS is that "It's unstable" or "crashes often" so I believe that stability should be a priority. Also simple plotting is welcome but I'd prefer a strong data manipulation library with a good integration with other specialized data visualization libraries because I feel that time spent focusing on visualization development is time not spend on data manipulation development, a little bit in line with the philosopy of a tool that does one job and does it well, rather than a swiss army knife that may not perform well on certain tasks.

column28:
First off, GeoPandas is an incredible project and hats off to the development team. My personal single biggest pain point is trying to use GeoPandas with Folium. In the R ecosystem the way that sf works with leaflet and mapview is simple and intuitive. I know that this isn't your package, but I'd love to see more examples of workflows that go from spatial data analysis, to quick and simple folium map. 

The only thing that keeps me in the R spatial ecosystem is that it is so easy to interactively view the results of a spatial analysis by quickly passing in a SF object to leaflet/mapview with a tooltip/hover

column28:
Matplotlib is a bear, so anything you can do to make plotting more intuitive and flexible without having to delve into matplotlib... anything at all! 
I've tried to access geopandas functionality from the console in QGIS - if there was a way to do this it would be extremely useful, as having to learn and relearn different APIs is a pain - the use case was bundling geopandas within a QGIS plugin, because we were working on something standalone in geopandas, but to reach a larger community delivering that functionality inside a GIS platform would be key. But maybe that's a QGIS feature request not a geopandas one.
Better integration with web-mapping platforms and frameworks would be very useful.
